Crowd Server receives the following validation factor in a {{isValidPrincipalToken}} API call:
{code}
<ValidationFactor xsi:nil="true" xmlns="http://authentication.integration.crowd.atlassian.com" />
{code}

At {{com.atlassian.crowd.authentication.TokenKeyGeneratorImpl.getFactor()}} a NullPointerException will be thrown:

{code}
    private ValidationFactor getFactor(List<ValidationFactor> validationFactors, String factorName)
    {
        for (Iterator<ValidationFactor> validationFactorIterator = validationFactors.iterator(); validationFactorIterator.hasNext();)
        {
            ValidationFactor validationFactor = validationFactorIterator.next();
            if (factorName.equals(validationFactor.getName()))
            {
                return validationFactor;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }
{code}

Solution suggestion:
1-) Add a {{validationFactor != null}} to the {{if}}
2-) Prevent the list population with null values

Crowd integration with Bamboo still has screwed up caches. (for a different reason from before now!)

The ehcache CacheManager is singleton, so is only ever created once.  We create it once for us using our own config file, when you guys call "createConfiguration(crowd-cache.xml)" it just returns to you the cache manager that was initially created (with our configuration, not yours).

{code}
public static CacheManager create(URL configurationFileURL) throws CacheException {
        if (singleton != null) {
            return singleton;
        }
        synchronized (CacheManager.class) {
            if (singleton == null) {
                if (LOG.isLoggable(Level.FINE)) {
                    LOG.fine("Creating new CacheManager with config URL: " + configurationFileURL);
                }
                singleton = new CacheManager(configurationFileURL);

            }
            return singleton;
        }
    }
{code}

(code snippet is from net.sf.ehcache.CacheManager, called from com.atlassian.crowd.integration.service.cache.CacheImpl)

The work around is to put all the crowd cache configuration stuff into Bamboo's ehcache.xml file.

